<section id="introduction">
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>Taoism (<span class="chinese-char">道</span>, <span class="pinyin">Dào</span>, "The Way") is China's indigenous philosophical and religious tradition — a vast river of thought, practice, and cosmology that has shaped Chinese civilisation for over two and a half thousand years. It exists in two interrelated but distinct forms: <strong>Daojia</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">道家</span>, Taoist philosophy) and <strong>Daojiao</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">道教</span>, Taoist religion).</p>
      <p>Taoist philosophy, rooted in the writings attributed to Laozi and Zhuangzi, addresses the fundamental nature of reality, the relationship between humans and the cosmos, and the art of living in harmony with natural processes. Taoist religion, formalised during the Han Dynasty, developed an elaborate system of temples, clergy, rituals, deities, and practices aimed at spiritual cultivation, health, and immortality.</p>
      <p>Together, these two streams form the cosmological bedrock of Chinese culture — the yin-yang principle, <a href="/wuxing/">Five Element theory</a>, qi cultivation, the <a href="/yijing/">Yi Jing</a>'s divinatory framework, <a href="/tcm/">traditional medicine</a>, <a href="/martial-arts/">internal martial arts</a>, and <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a> all draw deeply from Taoist thought.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="philosophy">
      <h2>Core Philosophy</h2>

      <h3>The Dao (<span class="chinese-char">道</span>, <span class="pinyin">Dào</span>)</h3>
      <p>The Dao is the central concept of Taoism — and simultaneously the one that resists definition. The <em>Daodejing</em> opens with the paradox: <strong>"道可道，非常道"</strong> (<span class="pinyin">Dào kě dào, fēi cháng dào</span>) — "The Way that can be spoken is not the eternal Way." The Dao is the formless, nameless source from which all things arise, the underlying pattern of the universe, and the principle by which all things naturally operate.</p>
      <div class="pullquote">
        The Dao is not a god, not a force, not a substance. It is the way things are before we impose categories upon them — the river before we name it, the season before we count it, the breath before we notice it.
      </div>

      <h3>De (<span class="chinese-char">德</span>, <span class="pinyin">Dé</span>)</h3>
      <p>De is the Dao's manifestation in individual things — the inherent nature or virtue of each being. A tree's De is to grow according to its nature; a river's De is to flow downward. For humans, De is the quality of being aligned with the Dao — not moral virtue in the Confucian sense, but the power that comes from acting in accordance with one's true nature.</p>

      <h3>Wu Wei (<span class="chinese-char">無為</span>, <span class="pinyin">Wú Wéi</span>)</h3>
      <p>Wu Wei, often translated as "non-action" or "effortless action," does not mean passivity. It means acting without forcing, without going against the grain of natural processes. The <em>Daodejing</em> uses the metaphor of water: water is soft and yielding, yet it wears away the hardest stone. Wu Wei is the art of achieving maximum effect through minimum intervention — a principle that deeply influences <a href="/martial-arts/#internal">internal martial arts</a> (especially Taijiquan) and <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a> practice.</p>

      <h3>Pu (<span class="chinese-char">朴</span>, <span class="pinyin">Pǔ</span>)</h3>
      <p>Pu, the "uncarved block," represents original simplicity — the state of things before they are shaped by human convention, desire, and knowledge. The Taoist ideal is to return to this state of natural simplicity, shedding the accumulated layers of social conditioning to rediscover one's original nature.</p>

      <h3>Ziran (<span class="chinese-char">自然</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zìrán</span>)</h3>
      <p>Ziran means "self-so" or "naturalness" — things being what they spontaneously are without external compulsion. The <em>Daodejing</em> states: "Humans follow Earth; Earth follows Heaven; Heaven follows the Dao; the Dao follows Ziran." Naturalness is thus the ultimate principle — even the Dao itself accords with it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="classics">
      <h2>Classical Texts</h2>

      <h3>Daodejing (<span class="chinese-char">道德經</span>, <span class="pinyin">Dàodéjīng</span>)</h3>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>The <em>Daodejing</em> (also known as the <em>Laozi</em>) is the foundational text of Taoism — a collection of 81 brief chapters totalling roughly 5,000 characters. Attributed to <strong>Laozi</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">老子</span>, "Old Master"), it was likely compiled during the late Warring States period (4th–3rd century BCE). It addresses the nature of the Dao, the art of governance, and the cultivation of personal wisdom through paradox, metaphor, and poetic compression.</p>
        <cite>— Laozi, <em>《道德經》</em>, late Warring States period (4th–3rd century BCE)</cite>
      </div>
      <p>Key themes include the power of softness over hardness, the danger of excessive knowledge, the superiority of effortless action, and the ruler's ideal of governing so lightly that the people are hardly aware of being governed. The text has been translated into more languages than any other work except the Bible.</p>

      <h3>Zhuangzi (<span class="chinese-char">莊子</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zhuāngzǐ</span>)</h3>
      <p>The <em>Zhuangzi</em>, attributed to <strong>Zhuang Zhou</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">莊周</span>, c. 369–286 BCE), is the second great Taoist classic — and one of the most brilliant works of Chinese literature. Where the <em>Daodejing</em> is terse and enigmatic, the <em>Zhuangzi</em> is expansive, playful, and wildly imaginative.</p>
      <p>Its 33 chapters (the "Inner Chapters" are considered most authentic) use stories, dialogues, jokes, and absurdist scenarios to dissolve conventional thinking. The famous butterfly dream — Zhuang Zhou dreams he is a butterfly, then wakes and wonders whether he is a man who dreamed of being a butterfly, or a butterfly now dreaming of being a man — is the most celebrated philosophical thought experiment in Chinese literature.</p>

      <h3>Liezi (<span class="chinese-char">列子</span>, <span class="pinyin">Lièzǐ</span>)</h3>
      <p>The <em>Liezi</em>, attributed to <strong>Lie Yukou</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">列禦寇</span>), is the third major Taoist philosophical text. It contains stories about immortals, the nature of reality, and fate. The famous parable of the "Old Man at the Frontier" (<span class="chinese-char">塞翁失馬</span>, <span class="pinyin">Sàiwēng Shī Mǎ</span>) — "blessings and misfortunes are intertwined" — originates from this text and encapsulates the Taoist view of fortune and adversity.</p>

      <h3>Baopuzi (<span class="chinese-char">抱朴子</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bàopǔzǐ</span>)</h3>
      <p>Written by <strong>Ge Hong</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">葛洪</span>, 283–343 CE) during the Jin Dynasty, the <em>Baopuzi</em> ("Master Who Embraces Simplicity") bridges Taoist philosophy and Taoist religion. Its "Inner Chapters" address alchemy, immortality techniques, talismans, and the cultivation of the elixir of life. Its "Outer Chapters" discuss Confucian ethics and governance. Ge Hong's work is the most important early source for understanding Taoist alchemical practice.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="immortals">
      <h2>The Eight Immortals (<span class="chinese-char">八仙</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bāxiān</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Eight Immortals are the most beloved figures in Chinese popular mythology — a diverse group of Taoist sages who achieved immortality through cultivation, virtue, or divine grace. They represent a cross-section of Chinese society: old and young, male and female, noble and humble, scholarly and martial.</p>

      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Immortal</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Attribute</th><th>Represents</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Lü Dongbin</td><td><span class="chinese-char">呂洞賓</span></td><td>Sword</td><td>Scholar-warrior, leader of the Eight</td></tr>
          <tr><td>He Xiangu</td><td><span class="chinese-char">何仙姑</span></td><td>Lotus flower</td><td>Young woman, purity and grace</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Zhongli Quan</td><td><span class="chinese-char">鍾離權</span></td><td>Fan</td><td>Military officer, alchemy master</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Li Tieguai</td><td><span class="chinese-char">李鐵拐</span></td><td>Iron crutch &amp; gourd</td><td>Disabled beggar, healing powers</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Zhang Guolao</td><td><span class="chinese-char">張果老</span></td><td>Paper donkey</td><td>Elderly sage, eccentricity</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Han Xiangzi</td><td><span class="chinese-char">韓湘子</span></td><td>Flute</td><td>Youth, music, joy</td></tr>
